    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Originalism is the legal philosophy that judges must interpret the Constitution based on the original public meaning of the text at the time it was adopted. Proponents argue this prevents judges from imposing their personal, subjective policy preferences onto the foundational law. By sticking to the framers' intent, originalism ensures the Constitution remains a fixed, stable document rather than a constantly shifting political tool. This approach is fundamentally about respecting the democratic will of the people as expressed at the time of ratification.",
      "source": "target",
